    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'll check the load balancer logs. i'm also wondering if it could be something at the OS level? like maybe the kernel is dropping packets or something? it's driving me crazy because it's so random. any idea what specifically in the networking stack would cause this kind of sudden drop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "At the OS level, random resets can point to TCP keepalive settings, network buffer overflows, or even kernel-level firewall rules (like `iptables` or `firewalld`) aggressively timing out connections. If the OS is dropping packets, sometimes it's due to resource exhaustion, like running out of ephemeral ports or memory. You might want to check system metrics like network interface errors or look into TCP stack tuning parameters on the EC2 instance.",
      "source": "target",
